---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';

const browserSdkExample = `import { IdrClient } from '@idrto/idr_browser_sdk';

const client = IdrClient.forService('ollama');
await client.ensureSession({ interactive: true, mount: document.getElementById('auth') });
await client.connect({ host: 'gpu-a.us-east.user-40acme-2Ecom.idr' });

const res = await client.fetch('/api/chat', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
  body: JSON.stringify({
    model: 'llama3.2',
    messages: [{ role: 'user', content: 'Summarize our Q3 edge strategy.' }],
    stream: true,
  }),
});`;

const streamExample = `const reader = res.body.getReader();
const decoder = new TextDecoder();
while (true) {
  const { done, value } = await reader.read();
  if (done) break;
  for (const line of decoder.decode(value).split('\\n')) {
    if (line.startsWith('data: ')) {
      const chunk = JSON.parse(line.slice(6));
      process.stdout.write(chunk.message?.content ?? '');
    }
  }
}`;

const accessKeyCurl = `curl -X POST https://idr.to/v1/access-keys \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer …" \\
  -d '{"label":"contractor-q3","scopes":["resolve","connect"]}'`;

const systemdUnit = `[Unit]
Description=idr.to target agent (Ollama host)
After=network-online.target ollama.service

[Service]
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/idr agent run
Restart=always
Environment=IDR_CONFIG=/etc/idrto/idr-agent.toml

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target`;

const verifyOllamaLocal = `curl http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/tags
curl http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/generate -d '{
  "model": "llama3.2",
  "prompt": "Hello from Austin edge",
  "stream": false
}'`;

const cliAccess = `# Source machine
idr auth login dev@acme.com
idr agent source   # optional background proxy

# Tunnel Ollama port (P2P, no data charges)
idr connect gpu-a.us-east.user-40acme-2Ecom.idr 11434 --local-port 11434 --duration 0

# Another terminal — same API as local Ollama
curl http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/tags
curl http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/chat -d '{
  "model": "llama3.2",
  "messages": [{"role":"user","content":"Edge RTT test"}],
  "stream": false
}'`;

const ragPipeline = `# On Mac Mini — embedding endpoint (same Ollama)
curl http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/embeddings -d '{
  "model": "nomic-embed-text",
  "prompt": "Quarterly revenue by region"
}'

# Remote developer via tunnel — identical URLs on localhost:11434
idr connect gpu-a.us-east.user-40acme-2Ecom.idr 11434 --local-port 11434`;
---

<Layout title="Case study: Ollama BYOM on M4 Mac Mini — idr.to">
  <Header slot="header" />
  <Footer slot="footer" />

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Case study · BYOM · AI workloads</p>
      <h1>Run Ollama on an M4 Mac Mini.<br />Use it from <em>anywhere.</em></h1>
      <p class="lead">
        A detailed BYOM walkthrough: local LLM inference on Apple Silicon at home or in a branch office, reachable by
        CLI, scripts, and browser apps — without opening port 11434 or shipping prompts through idr.to servers.
      </p>

      <h2>Scenario</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Acme AI</strong> (an ISV) sells a document assistant. Customers run <a href="https://ollama.com">Ollama</a>
        on their own M4 Mac Mini in Austin — models stay on-prem for latency, GPU utilization, and data residency.
        Acme needs:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Engineers calling <code>/api/chat</code> from laptops without VPN</li>
        <li>A web UI (Browser SDK) where users enter only their edge host name</li>
        <li>Scoped delegate access for contractors via access keys</li>
        <li>Optional public HTTPS URL for integrations that cannot use WebRTC</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Device-Identity &amp; globally addressable FQHN</h2>
      <p>When the Mac Mini registers:</p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Artifact</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Device-Identity</strong></td><td>Unique Device-ID from on-device Ed25519 keypair</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Registered host</strong></td><td><code>gpu-a.us-east</code> under entity <code>acme.com</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Synthetic FQHN</strong></td><td><code>gpu-a.us-east.user-40acme-2Ecom.idr</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Canonical URI</strong></td><td><code>idrto:gpu-a.us-east~acme.com/ollama</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>DEF FQHN (relay)</strong></td><td><code>dgpu-a-2eus-2deast-7eacme-2ecom.idr.to</code></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        Every device gets its own <strong>Device-Identity</strong>; every registered host gets an
        <strong>FQHN</strong> resolvable worldwide through idr.to. Multiple Mac Minis can share a host name —
        resolve round-robins like DNS A records.
      </p>

      <h2>Architecture</h2>
      <pre class="flow-diagram">┌─────────────────────┐         signaling (WSS)        ┌──────────────────┐
│  Developer laptop   │◄──────────────────────────────►│  idr.to hosted   │
│  idr agent (source) │                                │  registry+signal │
└─────────┬───────────┘                                └────────▲─────────┘
          │                                                     │
          │ WebRTC P2P (idr-tunnel)                             │ persistent WSS
          │ HTTP bytes → target :11434                          │
          ▼                                                     │
┌─────────────────────┐         ┌─────────────────┐              │
│  M4 Mac Mini        │         │  Browser (SDK)  │──────────────┘
│  Ollama :11434      │◄─ P2P ─│  BYOM web app   │
│  idr agent (target) │         └─────────────────┘
│  models on disk     │
└─────────────────────┘

Optional HTTPS relay (metered): curl → *.idr.to DEF FQHN → TLS pass-through → agent → Ollama</pre>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Data plane privacy:</strong> Prompts, completions, and embeddings travel P2P over WebRTC or as
        encrypted bytes through relay pass-through. idr.to signaling servers never see model I/O. If you later add
        HTTPS on Ollama behind nginx, Let's Encrypt private keys stay on the Mac Mini — same pass-through semantics.
      </div>

      <h2>Step 1 — Subscribe, Device-Identity &amp; host registration</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Create Enterprise entity <code>acme.com</code> (multi-level hosts for <code>gpu-a.us-east</code>).</li>
        <li>Install CLI: <code>curl -fsSL https://download.idr.to/install.sh | bash</code></li>
        <li>On the Mac Mini: <code>idr auth login admin@acme.com</code></li>
        <li>Register device (creates <strong>Device-Identity</strong>): <code>idr device register --name mac-mini-m4</code></li>
        <li>Register host (creates <strong>FQHN</strong> mapping): <code>idr host register gpu-a.us-east</code></li>
        <li>Start target agent: <code>idr agent run</code> (or launchd — see below)</li>
        <li>Install Ollama: <code>brew install ollama && ollama serve</code></li>
        <li>Pull models: <code>ollama pull llama3.2 && ollama pull nomic-embed-text</code></li>
      </ol>
      <pre><code>{systemdUnit}</code></pre>
      <p>On macOS use a LaunchDaemon with the same <code>idr agent run</code> command.</p>

      <h2>Step 2 — Verify Ollama locally</h2>
      <pre><code>{verifyOllamaLocal}</code></pre>
      <p>Ollama listens on loopback; no firewall hole required.</p>

      <h2>Step 3 — CLI access from a developer laptop</h2>
      <pre><code>{cliAccess}</code></pre>
      <p>Canonical URI resolved under the hood:</p>
      <pre><code>idrto:gpu-a.us-east~acme.com/ollama</code></pre>

      <h2>Step 4 — BYOM browser app (ISV integration)</h2>
      <p>
        Acme hardcodes the Ollama service at build time; end-users only enter their edge FQHN and sign in:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{browserSdkExample}</code></pre>
      <p>
        The SDK opens a WebRTC tunnel and sends HTTP/1.1 to <code>127.0.0.1:11434</code> on the Mac Mini.
        Streaming responses work unchanged:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{streamExample}</code></pre>

      <h3>BYOM checklist for ISVs</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Who owns it</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>GPU / Mac hardware</td><td>Customer</td><td>M4 Neural Engine + unified memory</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Ollama + model weights</td><td>Customer</td><td>Never uploaded to Acme or idr.to</td></tr>
            <tr><td>idr target agent</td><td>Customer</td><td>Outbound WSS only</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Browser SDK (~11 KB gzip)</td><td>Acme (ISV)</td><td><code>IdrClient.forService('ollama')</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Auth UI</td><td>idr.to SDK shadow DOM</td><td>Access keys never in ISV JS</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Inference traffic</td><td>P2P WebRTC</td><td>Free; no relay metering</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p><a href="/isv">Full ISV / BYOM guide →</a></p>

      <h2>Step 5 — RAG pipeline on the same edge box</h2>
      <p>Many BYOM deployments co-locate embedding + vector search with chat:</p>
      <pre><code>{ragPipeline}</code></pre>
      <p>
        A local Chroma or sqlite-vec instance on <code>127.0.0.1:8000</code> can be exposed with
        <code>idrto:gpu-a.us-east~acme.com/8000</code> — same Device-Identity and FQHN, different port segment.
      </p>

      <h2>Step 6 — Delegate access with access keys</h2>
      <pre><code>{accessKeyCurl}</code></pre>
      <p>
        Contractor pastes <code>idr_ak_…</code> into the SDK auth panel — scoped to resolve/connect for
        <code>gpu-a.us-east</code> only. No VPN, no shared SSH keys.
      </p>

      <h2>When the network blocks P2P</h2>
      <p>
        Strict corporate Wi‑Fi may block direct ICE. Options:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>TURN bundle</strong> (500 GB / US$10) — WebRTC relay through <code>turn.idr.to</code>; still encrypted, metered.</li>
        <li><strong>HTTPS relay</strong> — for clients that only speak TLS to a public hostname:</li>
      </ol>
      <pre><code>https://dgpu-a-2eus-2deast-7eacme-2ecom.idr.to/ollama/api/chat</code></pre>
      <p>
        Relay reads SNI only; TLS is pass-through if you terminate on nginx/Ollama with a Let's Encrypt cert issued
        on-device. Relay bytes count against bundles; pure P2P does not.
      </p>

      <h2>Results</h2>
      <div class="card-grid card-grid--3">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Latency</h3>
          <p>Tokens generated on M4 locally; network adds RTT only — no cloud inference hop.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Security</h3>
          <p>Device-Identity per machine; ACLs at resolve; prompts never stored on idr.to; no inbound ports.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Cost</h3>
          <p>Enterprise US$50/user/year; GPU power is customer OpEx; relay bundles only when needed.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/isv">ISV integration guide</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/case-study/nginx">nginx + Node.js case study</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/evaluate">Start evaluation</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  h1 { font-size: 2.25rem; margin: 0 0 1rem; }
  h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem; }
  h3 { font-size: 1.0625rem; margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }
  ol, ul { color: var(--text-muted); padding-left: 1.25rem; }
  .card p { color: var(--text-muted); margin: 0; font-size: 0.9375rem; }
</style>
